{"/service/ndnp/wyu/batch_wyu_alcott_ver01/data/sn92066979/00513687485/1908032501/0289.xml":{"full_text":"One Book In a Thousand, \u201cThe Shepard of the Hills.\u201d A Beautiful Story Well Told. A Pleasure to Recommend It. $1.50 the Copy.\n\u00fc\u00df e DRUGS, stationery and magazines.\n>-7 IL.\nLW*^k <Xt /xivJy'\n\\\u00abp _<t<\u00ab A 4/vk\nC><>\u00bb wFy\n~Bcgr\nMesdames Davis DeLario Ofg@\nannounce the formal opening IgHsf.\nBsfajh-.\nof their entirely new stock of\nMillinery and Accessories for\nk'v\nThursday, Friday and Sat-\nurday of this week, March YMO*\n26th, 27th and 28th, 217\nSecond Street. u 4 h&AFJ\nRnV-'<\nGOING AFTER DUCKS?\nY\nAutomatic Repeating Shotguns\nL. C. Smith and Ithaca Double-barrel\nShotguns\nWinchester Repeating Shotguns\n\nJ A Full Line of\nAmmunition and Gun Supplies\nAt the\n|W.H. HOLLIDAY CO.\neeeeeeeeeeeee*\nAbout Insurance\nWell, we are ready to write that insurance for you, fire, life or\naccident. There is a lot of satisfaction in naving insurance in good\nline companies. We have seen tc that. So make us a call when your\npolicy expires. We will treat you right.\nHave you M)ld that ranch or town property? We have calls near,\nly every day for the right kind at the right price.\nTHE LARAMIE REALTY CO.,\nRoom* 1 and 2, Miller Block.\nPRUSSIAN STOCK FOOD\nNone Other as Good.\nCOOLICAN BROS.\nWE ARE\nHERE\nMILLS\u2019 UNIVERSITY BOOK STORE\nGRADUATE PHILADELPHIA COLLEGE OF PHARMACY.\nNOT GOING\nTOJSLANDS\nSECOND LIEUTENANT RICE ASKS\nTO HAVE REPUBLICAN CON\nTINUED TO SAME PLACE.\nSeventh Infantry Expected to Leave for\nSan Francisco on Sunday and Sai!\nfrom That Port on Following Mon\nday, But Orders from War Depart,\nment Bring Change.\nI Second Lieutenant C. H. Rice of the\nSeventh United States infantry at Fort\nBrady, Mich., in a note to the business\ndepartment of The Republican,\ndate of March 22, says: \u201cSine 2 the\nwar department has seen fit to continue\nour service in the United States for\nanother year, please do not change the\naddress of my paper to Manila, P. i.,\nas requested in my letter of the :sth,\nbut continue sending it to Fort Brady.\nWe were to depart from this station\non March 29. Everything was in read\niness, all furniture and property pack\ned ready for shipment, the troops sup\nplied with khaki for tropical wear and\nthe regiment recruited to iis tull\nstrength. We were to sail from San\nFrancisco on April 6, but orders receiv\ned yesterday slate that we shall sail\nin April, 1909. The Republican will\nstill be warmly welcomed at Fort Bra\ndy.\u201d The Republican will still contin\nue to go to Lieutenant Rice at that\npost.\nWill Inspect Cadets.\nThe following military order was is\nsued from the war department at\nWashington yesterday, and will be of\nlocal interest:\nCaptain Julius A. Penn, general staff,\nwill go to the University of Wyoming,\nLaramie, and the state agricultural\ncollege of Colorado at Fort Collins, for\nthe puiirort of making the annual in\nspection of the military departments\nof these educational institutions.\nGoing to Yellowstone.\ni Captain Wallace Dewitt, assistant\nsurgeqn in the United States army,\nhas been ordered to Fort Yellowstone,\nYellowstone National park, for duty.\nGoing to Fort Russell.\nCaptain John W. Heavey, late mili\ntary commandant at the University cf\nWyoming, who has been ordered to\njoin his regiment, the Eleventh infan\ntry, will leave toward the end of the\nweek for Fort D A. Russell, the home\npost of the regiment, and will prob\nably go from there to Cuba, his com\npany, E, being stationed at Holguin, in\nthat republic. Lieutenant John Hill of\nthe experiment station will succeed\nCaptain Heavey in command of the ca\ndets for the remainder of the univer\nsity year.\n\nhome from mines\nAFTER BUSINESS VISIT.\nFormer Mayor A. E- Miller, who is\none of the officers of the Citizens\u2019 Coal\ncompany, returned last night from Hat\nton, where he had been looking after\nthe development of the company\u2019s\nmines. Mt. Miller is arranging to take\na party of citizens to the mines on\nSunday, if the weather Is propitious.\nPILES CURED IN 6TO 14 DAYS.\nPAZO OINTMENT Is guaranteed to\ncure and cast of Itching, Blind, Bleed\ning or Protruding Piles In 6 to 14 days\nor money refunded. 60c. mwl\nI\nWeekly Republican only |j a year.\nTHE LARAMIE REPUBLICAN, DAILY EDITION\u2014 Wednesday, march 25, 1908.\nCONFIDENCE\nIN COUNTRY\nTRAFFIC MANAGER STUBBS OF\nHARRIMAN SYSTEM SAYS PEO\nPLE ARE NOT ALARMED.\nBeleves There is Return of Prosperity\nin Short Time and That Railroads\nWill Soon Be Moving Vast Amount\nof Freight\u2014Railroad Companies\nSued for Neglecting Stock.\nJ. C. Stubbs, head of the traffic de\npartment of the Harriman lines, arriv\ned in Omaha Monday morning and will\ngo to Lincoln Tuesday to attend the\nmeeting of the Nebraska railway com\nmission when the question of the ad\nvisability of putting in distance tariffs\nin Nebraska will be considered, says\nthe Omaha Bee. The commission had\nconsidered the idea of taking up this\nquestion, but P. A. Caldwell of Edgar\nforesaw the action and filed an appli\ncation with the commission asking that\nit show cause why such rates could not\nbe installed in Nebraska.\nCountry All Right.\n\u2018\u2019This country of ours is all right.\nsaid J. C. Stubbs, who did not look al\nthough the care of thousands of men\nwas on his shoulders as he walked up\nthe street in a new gray suit. \u201cThe peo\nple have confidence in the country,\nthere is plenty of money here and it is\nonly a master of time until they go to\nspending it again. The merchants are\nsimply holding back and letting the;\nstocks run down to the lowest point o i\nwhich they can do business, but the\nthings will change and when they do\nstart to buy they will have to buy hea\nvy and business will open up with a\nrush. It may go a little slow for some\ntime, but there is no doubt of its re\nturning.\u201d\nMr. Stubbs said that he had simply\ncome to Omaha to attend the meeting\nat Lincoln and that there was absolute\nly no other significance in his visit at\nthis time.\nRailroad Companies Sued.\nSuit was filed at Ogden Monday by\nM. A. Thomas, through his attorneys,\nMaginnis Corn, against the Oregon\nShort Line and Union Pacific Railway\ncompanies for $3,280 damages which\nThomas claims he sustained through\nthe carelessness of the companies\nwhile transferring 1,480 head of sheep\nfrom Opal, Wyo., to Omaha, Neb., in\nOctober, 190 G. Thomas charges the\nrailroads with negligently failing and\ni efusing to properly care for the stock\nfrom the time it was placed aboard a\ntrain until the destination of the ship\nment was reached. Fifteen head died\nin transit, according to the complaint,\nthrough the lack of prater attention.\nAttacks Demurrage Law.\nW. R. Begg, general solicitor of the\nGreat Northern railway, in a letter to\nAttorney General Young of Minnesota\nat St. Paul, attacks the reciprocal de\nmurrage law passed by the last Minne\nsota legislature, and state officials in\nfer from his letter that the railroad\ncompany will contest the law on con\nstitutional grounds.\nSTOP THE STRENUOUS LIFE\nWeakens the Tissues and Lessens\nOrganic Vitality.\nThe stress and strain of the strenu\nous life in both city and country tends\ntowards stomach troubles. Five peo\nple suffer today where one did ten\nyears ago with sick headache, dizzi\nness, flatulence, distress after eating,\nspecks before the eyes, bloating, ner\nvousness, sleeplessness and the many\nother symptoms of indigestion.\nAll who are suffering with stomach\ntroubles, and that means at least two\nout of three in Laramie and other\ntowns should use Mi-o-na stomacli\ntablets. Nothing else can be ro\nthoroughly relied upon to relieve nil\ntroubles from indigestion as Mi-o-na.\nSo reliable is Mi-o-na in its curatve\naction that-the Laramie Drug company\nwith every 50-cent box it sells, gives\na guarantee to refund the money un\nless the remedy cures.\nLOOK HERE! THIS WAY!\nIf you want a bargain in ranch lands\nimproved or unimproved\u2022 in city prop\nerty, furnished or unfurnished; if you\nwant to buy a business or loan your\nmoney on best of security, call on\nLZL T. TJZjEKT\nJ. I ALLYN,\nCARPENTER\nand\nCONTRACTOR\nEighth and University Avenue.\nCement Block Houses a Specialty\nCome and get my figures If you are\ncontemplating building and see how\ncheap I can put up a handsome cement\nblock house; never needs to be paint,\ned; warm In winter, cool in summer.\nAlso cement outside steps, ash pits,\ncoping for graves and lawns at a rea\nsonable price.\nPERSONAL PARAGRAPHS\nOle Anderson is at the Johnson\nL. Keyes of Tie Siding Is in the\ncity.\nMr s Weaver went to Tie Siding to\nday.\nOtto Gramm went to Cheyenne to\nday.\nL. B. Hoppe of Sheridan is in the\ncity.\nMrs. J. W. Connor went to Denver\ntoday.\nGeorge Eykyn has returned from his\neastern trip.\nMrs. Dunham of Pocatello, Idaho, is\nat the Kuster.\nWilliam Mathis is at the Kuster\nfrom Cheyenne.\nMr. and Mrs. Marsh Atwell returned\nfrom Cheyenne today.\nJohn C. Fulton of Chicago was here\nthis morning, registered at the Kuster.\nMr. and Mrs. Archie McPhee and\nfamily have returned from Arcadia,\nI Neb.\nMr. and Mrs. Richard Tregoning re\nturned from a week\u2019s visit at Denver\ntoday.\nJ. F. Vuagniaux of Gleneyre was a\ncity visitor last night, registered at the\nJohnson.\nP. S. Newcombe, the well known pa\nper salesman, is in the city today, call\ning on the trade.\nWilliam B. Oliver and E. E. Whit -I\nman of New York were among the\nguests at the Kuster last night.\nMr and Mrs. E. D. Hiskey left last\nnight for Salem, 0., where their moth\ner, Mrs. Dillenbeck, is quite ill.\nE.l O. Moen of Virginia dale was here\nthis morning, coming yesterday with\nranch supplies for his local trade.\nMiss Maggie Blair has resumed her\nposition at the Three Rules. Miss\nBlair has been at Excelsior Springs,\nMo., taking treatment.\nW. S. Whittingham and James\nOwens, the Morgan mining men, return\ned home today, after a short business\ntrip to the county seat.\nC. P. Lund, Miss Myrtle Seggerman,\nMr. and Mrs. A. C. Phillips and Miss\nisora Phillips of Mandel were among\nthe visitors here today.\nAndrew Kiser went co Centennial\nthis morning and will take a position\nwith J. F. White\u2019s grading gang on the\nLaramie Plains extension south from\nthat place\nWilliam Benton, the Centennial min\ning man, arrived from that place yes\nterday afternoon and left today for\nCheyenne on a short business trip to\nthe state capital.\nG. C. Mason of Centennial, one ut\nthe trustees of the new Pollyton Gold\nMining company, whose articles wen?\nfiled here today, was in the city la>i\nnight, leaving for home this morning.\nWalter Hixon and H. T. Webber, who\ncame to town a day or two ago with\nlumber for the local yards, returned\nhome today, the hauling cf lumber\nhaving been brought to an en 1 for the\npresent.\nMr. and Mrs. J. C. Luking have ar\nrived from Farmer City, 111., and will\nmake their home at. the Blackburn\nranch. Mr. Lucking is a blacksmith\nby occupation and will follow that call\ning at the ranch.\nW. O. Stanley of San Francisco, trav\neling for the Schilling Manufacturing\ncompany, attended the funeral of bls\ncousin, Charles Stanley, who was kill\ned at Sidney, Neb., on the 19th. Mr.\nStanley was here today, looking after\nhis trade in this city.\nN. J. Couchot of Denver, traveling\nrepresentative of the Avery unction\nengine, was here this morning, interest\ning the Laramie Development company\nofficials in the engine for use on the\nBlackburn and other ranches during\nthe plowing and harvesting season.\nC. R. Root of the Swift company was\nhere this morning, and declared that\nwhile he was a good Christian and be\nlieved in Lent, he could not but notice\nthat the season made a difference with\nthe meat trade. However, be is satis\nfled. \u201cWe sell considerable stuff just\nthe same,\u201d he said.\nSIOO Reward SIOO.\nThe readers cf t